abstract={Tillage systems are rotated among crops for various reasons, including optimizing yields and managing pest and disease problems. This study indicates that growers in the central and northern Corn Belt regions practice tillage rotation frequently and that the longest average time that 1999 fields were maintained in continuous no-till is slightly less than 2.5 years in Illinois and Indiana and only 1.4 years in Minnesota. Compared with continuous no-till, rotational tillage can prevent or delay improvements in some soil physical and chemical properties (e.g. development of long-term macropores and increased organic matter). However, compared with continuous tillage, rotational tillage does allow for increased protection from soil erosion processes in alternating years. Growers appear to have experimented with no-till practices on a relatively high percentage of the fields as much as 77 percent of the fields sampled in Indiana. This is not surprising given how long crop residue management practices have been promoted by various conservation groups and private industry. No-till practices were developed in the 1950's and were promoted heavily in the early 1980's with the advent of the 1995 Farm Bill and the Conservation Compliance provision that required growers with highly erodible lands to maintain high levels of residue cover in return for continued government subsidy support. But given the relatively high use of rotational tillage, growers apparently are not satisfied with or simply aren't interested in practicing continuous no-till in corn-soybean rotations. While it is not within the scope of the this paper to understand why retrenchment occurs among adoption of certain landuse practices, it is important to realize in the context of improving land conservation that growers don't appear to have the desire and/or ability to use continuous no-till to the degree that may be necessary to sequester substantial amounts of carbon in order to help offset increased greenhouse gas emissions or to manage high levels of residue cover on an annual basis that may be needed to reduce long-term soil erosion rates to below tolerable levels. Producers will adopt continuous no-till practices on cropland where they perceive it is economically and agronomically feasible. The fact that rotational tillage is used widely across the Corn Belt indicates that one or more factors or barriers prevent the use of continuous no-till. Given greater acceptance of no-till soybean practices, particularly in the central and eastern Corn Belt, new or redirected research and extension efforts should focus on improving no-till corn production systems or variations of the no-till design such as strip-till systems that seem to incorporate the efficiencies of no-till systems with fertilizer management and the high yield environments often associated with conventional, full width tillage (Carter, 1994; Randall and Hill, 2000; Wolkowski, 1997). Extension of crop rotations beyond monoculture and two-year corn-soybean rotations can also help improve or alleviate concerns associated with undesirable planting conditions often associated with no-till environments (Griffith et al., 1988; Janovicek et al., 1997). It is unclear, however, whether markets exist that would allow production of crops other than corn and soybeans on significant acreage or whether government programs would encourage or support it. Regardless, long-term conservation goals may not be realized if growers can not or will not use conservation practices on a continual basis, thus allowing interruptions in improvement of soil properties and intermittently allowing soil and environmental degradation to occur.},
