abstract={Nutrient losses in runoff and eroded sediments from ten soils in the central eastern Nigeria were studied with simulated rainfall at the intensity of 180 mm ·h-1 for 60 min on micro-plots at 3% slope. The soils varied in their physical properties and are low in plant nutrients. Nutrient losses in the runoff ranged from 0.010 to 0.109 kg· m-2 with NO3-N, Mg and Ca higher than PO4-P and K. Organic carbon (OC) loss in the eroded sediments is high with values of 0.02 to 2.79 kg·m-2 and correlated positively (r=0.914) with soil OC. Similarly soil available P and exchangeable Ca correlated positively with the eroded sediment values (r=0.682 and 0.826), respectively. Higher enrichment ratio obtained for N and P imply potential environmental consequences like eutrophication of lakes and rivers.},
