The total and extractable concentrations and mass loadings of copper, lead, and zinc were determined at two soil depths in a nonindustrial urban watershed in Manoa, HI. Soil samples were collected at 88 randomly distributed locations within the watershed. Significantly higher topsoil cation exchange capacity, electrical conductivity, and organic carbon were noted compared to the subsoil samples, while pH and bulk density were higher in the subsoil layers. No statistical differences in Cu, Pb, and Zn concentrations were found between the topsoil and subsoil, with Zn found at the highest concentrations, followed by Cu and Pb. Subsoil loadings for total and extractable metals, however, were significantly greater than their topsoil equivalents. Lead and Zn, and to a lesser extent Cu, were anthropogenically enhanced in both the topsoil and subsoil layers. The metal mass per area enrichment ratios for all three metals indicated that the trace metals were mobile and that significant translocation had occurred.},
