abstract={Soil temperature affects crop growth through its impact on nutrient and water availability, yet few studies have quantitatively analyzed the effects of erosion on soil temperature regime. Therefore, this study was conducted to determine the impact of soil erosion on diurnal temperature fluctuations, and develop a simple model for predicting soil temperature regime from soil properties. Measurements of soil properties were made on four erosion classes established on Rhodic Ferrasol on the basis of the thickness of Ap horizon under natural field conditions. Fourier series analysis and boundary conditions obtained from observed temperature data were used to develop the model for predicting soil temperature. Results obtained indicate that soil erosion exposes subsoil, reduces soil organic carbon and moisture content. For dry soil condition, the heat capacity was 0.26 cal/cm3°C for severely eroded and 0.23 cal/cm3°C for slightly eroded class. The maximum soil temperature was about 1°C lower at 5 cm depth and 0.5°C at 30 cm depth for least compared with severely eroded phase. At field capacity, volumetric heat capacity was 0.53 cal/cm3°C for severely eroded and 0.57 cal/cm3°C for least eroded phase. Fourier series analysis can be used to predict soil temperature under different soil conditions by applying an appropriate boundary condition.},
