abstract={In areas surrounding the Matengo highlands, a ridge (Matuta) system of tillage is practised in conjunction with the more traditional Ngoro pit system. As in the Ngoro system, all vegetation prior to hand tillage is slashed and the residues are roughly aligned across the hillside, with soil thrown down the slope to form a ridge over the organic residues (ridge+OM), if labour is limiting the organic residues are burnt prior to ridge construction (ridge-OM). Both systems are said by the respective exponents to conserve moisture in soil, reduce soil erosion and where organic residues are incorporated improve soil fertility. A survey of 20 fields with Ngoro and 25 fields with Matuta on slopes ranging between 2 and 50% suggests that erosion occurred on less than 25% Ngoro fields, compared to 72% of fields under the Matuta ridges. On the Ngoro fields sheet erosion was dominant, with only one field having a gully. However, in all five fields, the erosion process was caused by water moving into the site from uncultivated fields above. This was in contrast to fields with the Matuta ridge system, where gullying was the dominant form of erosion. In fact erosion only failed to occur on those ridges aligned on the contour or combined with live barriers. In the Ngoro system, the majority of soil was redeposited in the pits, meaning a small, if any, nett loss of soil, but in the ridge systems much of the soil was transported out of the study areas. On a seasonal basis no statistical differences were observed in the amount of water stored under Ngoro, ridge+OM or ridges-OM or crop yields over three fields with slopes of 14%, 38% and 45%. Nevertheless, over three seasons of observation the Ngoro consistently yielded more beans and maize than either of the ridged systems, which produced similar quantities of beans. Maize yields on the ridges+OM was higher than ridges-OM. Although the monitoring period was not long enough to detect any major differences in soil chemistry, levels of organic Carbon were slightly higher under the ridge+OM than the other two systems, although this was not statistically significant. Economic analysis has indicated that Ngoro provides highest productivity where fertiliser is not applied, though at low soil fertility levels all systems are likely to give negative gross margins. Where fertiliser is applied the Matuta ridge systems are likely to give higher returns. Future work must be concentrated on the introduction of field boundary management techniques that prevent water shed from land above entering fields and creating erosion problems. Alignment of tillage systems, particularly the ridges along the contour and introduce some form of physical or a biological barrier than can reduce slope lengths. Lastly, but more importantly the farmers must be empowered to understand the economic value of fertilisers and organic residues and be encouraged not to burn it.},
