abstract={This study was conducted at three-year-old and seven-year-old sites which were afforested and had varying surface structures, i.e. crests and troughs. The average difference in elevation between crest and trough was 80 cm, between crests the average distance was 150 cm. Erosion of the bare soil led to an accumulation of silt and clay particles within the troughs. As a consequence, physical and chemical properties of the soil such as actual water content and the content of the exchangable macronutrients PO 4 3-P, K +, Ca 2+ varied between crests and troughs within three-year-old sites (always p &lt; 0.05). In addition, we found a higher carbon (C(org)) and NO 3(-)-N content of the soil in the troughs than in the crests (always p &lt; 0.01). Dry weight of the leaf litter, water retention capacity and the NH 4(+)-N content were significantly different (always p &lt; 0.01) between the crests and the troughs of the seven-year-old sites. Microbial respiration and biomass increased during the course of the succession for both types of surface formations (always p &lt; 0.001). Microbial biomass of the troughs was 1.5 times higher than the crests at the three-year-old sites and 3.0 times higher at the seven-year-old sites. Enchytraeidae, Collembola and Chironomidae were most common at three-year-old sites. Significantly higher densities (p &lt; 0.01) in the troughs were only observed for Collembola. Individuals of several families of Diptera such as Bibionidae, Tipulidae, Sciaridae and Faniidae were most common at the seven-year-old sites, whereby the densities of all families were significantly higher in the troughs than in the crests (always p &lt; 0.05). There was a correlation between the soil organic carbon content (C(org)), the biomass of the Tipulidae (r(s) = 0.743, p &lt; 0.001, n = 16) and the biomass of the microorganisms (r(s) = 0.793, p &lt; 0.001, n = 20) as well. Moreover, we found a correlation between microbial biomass and macronutrients (NO 3(-)-N, r(s) = 0.789, p &lt; 0.001; NH 4(+)-N, r(s) = 0.490, p &lt; 0.05), and the actual water content was correlated with the biomass of Tipulidae (r(s) = 0.551, p &lt; 0.05) and the biomass of microorganisms (r(s) = 0.493, p &lt; 0.05).},
