abstract={This paper presents field and column experiments to determine the fate of radionuclides (238U, 226Ra and 210Pb) and Mn, when applied in uranium mine waste water sprayed on to highly weathered soils near the Ranger uranium mine at Jabiru, Northern Territory, Australia. The radionuclides were retained in the surface few centimetres of soil. 238U and 210Pb did not remain in exchangeable forms after reaction with the soil, and there is little likelihood of them moving with water. 226Ra was also retained in the surface of the soils and did not move, but it contrasted with the other radionuclides in that &gt; 14% of the total was in the exchangeable form which may be available for uptake by roots. The field experiment with 22Na and 54Mn tracers showed that Na was readily leached out of the soil by wet season rains and 54Mn was slightly more mobile than the radionuclides. In the soil column experiment 54Mn was transported rapidly and this was related to saturation of sorption sites by very high loading rates. For the surface (0-4 cm) horizon, which had more organic carbon than subsurface horizons, transport was promoted by reduction caused by saturation of the soil. Although more mobile than the radionuclides, Mn is unlikely to reach the groundwater if applied to the soils tested under field conditions. The radionuclides will remain at the surface of the soil, and although this is advantageous in preventing their accessions to groundwater, it has the disadvantage that the radionuclides are exposed to mobilisation with soil subject to wind and water erosion, to uptake by plants and to ingestion by foraging animals.},
